  "cells": [
    {
      "id": "md-part1",
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": "---\n## Warm-Up\n\nThese cells test your understanding of lambda syntax and functional interfaces **without requiring you to write much code**.\nRead carefully, predict the output, then run to check.",
      "metadata": {
        "language": "markdown",
        "id": "md-part1"
      }
    },
    {
      "id": "md-1a",
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": "### Exercise 1a — Fix the broken lambdas\n\nEach cell below contains one broken lambda. Fix the syntax error and run the cell to confirm it passes.\nEvery case demonstrates a different rule — read the comment before editing.",
      "metadata": {
        "language": "markdown",
        "id": "md-1a"
      }
    },
    {
      "id": "md-1a-i",
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": "**1a-i** — Explicit type on a single parameter requires parentheses around the parameter list.",
      "metadata": {
        "language": "markdown",
        "id": "md-1a-i"
      }
    },
    {
      "id": "code-1a-i",
      "cell_type": "code",
      "source": "import java.util.function.*;\n\nFunction<String, Integer> lenOf = s -> s.length();\n\n// --- do not edit below ---\nassert lenOf.apply(\"hello\") == 5 : \"lenOf(hello) should be 5\";\nSystem.out.println(\"1a-i passed!\");",
      "metadata": {
        "language": "java",
        "id": "code-1a-i",
        "executionSummary": {
          "executionOrder": 2,
          "success": true
        }
      },
      "execution_count": 2,
      "outputs": [
        {
          "output_type": "execute_result",
          "data": {
            "text/plain": "1a-i passed!\r\n"
          },
          "metadata": {},
          "execution_count": 2
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": "md-1a-ii",
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": "**1a-ii** — Two parameters always require parentheses around the parameter list, even when types are omitted.",
      "metadata": {
        "language": "markdown",
        "id": "md-1a-ii"
      }
    },
    {
      "id": "code-1a-ii",
      "cell_type": "code",
      "source": "import java.util.function.*;\n\nBiFunction<Integer, Integer, Integer> add = (a, b) -> a + b;\n\n// --- do not edit below ---\nassert add.apply(3, 4) == 7 : \"add(3, 4) should be 7\";\nSystem.out.println(\"1a-ii passed!\");",
      "metadata": {
        "language": "java",
        "id": "code-1a-ii",
        "executionSummary": {
          "executionOrder": 3,
          "success": true
        }
      },
      "execution_count": 3,
      "outputs": [
        {
          "output_type": "execute_result",
          "data": {
            "text/plain": "1a-ii passed!\r\n"
          },
          "metadata": {},
          "execution_count": 3
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": "md-1a-iii",
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": "**1a-iii** — You cannot mix typed and untyped parameters. Either all parameters have explicit types, or none do.",
      "metadata": {
        "language": "markdown",
        "id": "md-1a-iii"
      }
    },
    {
      "id": "code-1a-iii",
      "cell_type": "code",
      "source": "import java.util.function.*;\n\nBiFunction<String, Integer, String> repeat = (s, n) -> s.repeat(n);\n\n// --- do not edit below ---\nassert repeat.apply(\"ab\", 3).equals(\"ababab\") : \"repeat(ab, 3) should be ababab\";\nSystem.out.println(\"1a-iii passed!\");",
      "metadata": {
        "language": "java",
        "id": "code-1a-iii",
        "executionSummary": {
          "executionOrder": 4,
          "success": true
        }
      },
      "execution_count": 4,
      "outputs": [
        {
          "output_type": "execute_result",
          "data": {
            "text/plain": "1a-iii passed!\r\n"
          },
          "metadata": {},
          "execution_count": 4
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": "md-1a-iv",
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": "**1a-iv** — A block body (with curly braces) requires an explicit `return` statement when the functional interface's method returns a value.",
      "metadata": {
        "language": "markdown",
        "id": "md-1a-iv"
      }
    },
    {
      "id": "code-1a-iv",
      "cell_type": "code",
      "source": "import java.util.function.*;\n\nFunction<Integer, Integer> triple = x -> { return x * 3; };\n\n// --- do not edit below ---\nassert triple.apply(7) == 21 : \"triple(7) should be 21\";\nSystem.out.println(\"1a-iv passed!\");",
      "metadata": {
        "language": "java",
        "id": "code-1a-iv",
        "executionSummary": {
          "executionOrder": 5,
          "success": true
        }
      },
      "execution_count": 5,
      "outputs": [
        {
          "output_type": "execute_result",
          "data": {
            "text/plain": "1a-iv passed!\r\n"
          },
          "metadata": {},
          "execution_count": 5
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": "md-1a-v",
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": "**1a-v** — A block body requires a semicolon after the last statement before the closing brace.",
      "metadata": {
        "language": "markdown",
        "id": "md-1a-v"
      }
    },
    {
      "id": "code-1a-v",
      "cell_type": "code",
      "source": "import java.util.function.*;\n\nPredicate<String> isEmpty = s -> { return s.isEmpty(); };\n\n// --- do not edit below ---\nassert isEmpty.test(\"\")    : \"isEmpty(\\\"\\\") should be true\";\nassert !isEmpty.test(\"hi\") : \"isEmpty(hi) should be false\";\nSystem.out.println(\"1a-v passed!\");",
      "metadata": {
        "language": "java",
        "id": "code-1a-v",
        "executionSummary": {
          "executionOrder": 6,
          "success": true
        }
      },
      "execution_count": 6,
      "outputs": [
        {
          "output_type": "execute_result",
          "data": {
            "text/plain": "1a-v passed!\r\n"
          },
          "metadata": {},
          "execution_count": 6
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": "md-1a-vi",
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": "**1a-vi** — The lambda body must match the return type of the functional interface. `Consumer<T>`'s `accept` method returns `void`, so the body should *do something* with the value rather than return it. This lambda is called `printer` — what might a printer do with a String?",
      "metadata": {
        "language": "markdown",
        "id": "md-1a-vi"
      }
    },
    {
      "id": "code-1a-vi",
      "cell_type": "code",
      "source": "import java.util.function.*;\n\nConsumer<String> printer = s -> { System.out.println(s); };\n// --- do not edit below ---\nprinter.accept(\"test\");  // should run without throwing\nSystem.out.println(\"1a-vi passed!\");",
      "metadata": {
        "language": "java",
        "id": "code-1a-vi",
        "executionSummary": {
          "executionOrder": 7,
          "success": true
        }
      },
      "execution_count": 7,
      "outputs": [
        {
          "output_type": "execute_result",
          "data": {
            "text/plain": "test\r\n1a-vi passed!\r\n"
          },
          "metadata": {},
          "execution_count": 7
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": "md-1b",
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": "### Exercise 1b — Choosing the right functional interface\n\nMatch each lambda to a predefined functional interface from `java.util.function`.\n\n**Task:** Replace each `???` with the correct interface type (`Supplier`, `Consumer`, `Predicate`, `Function`, `BiFunction`, or `BiConsumer`).\n\nYou do **not** need to change the lambda expressions themselves.",
      "metadata": {
        "language": "markdown",
        "id": "md-1b"
      }
    },
    {
      "id": "code-1b",
      "cell_type": "code",
      "source": "import java.util.function.*;\n\n// Takes a String, returns its uppercased version\nFunction <String, String> toUpper = s -> s.toUpperCase();\n\n// Takes an Integer, returns true if it is even\nPredicate <Integer> isEven = n -> n % 2 == 0;\n\n// Takes no argument, returns the string \"hello\"\nSupplier <String> greeter = () -> \"hello\";\n\n// Takes a String, prints it, returns nothing\nConsumer <String> printer = s -> System.out.println(\">> \" + s);\n\n// Takes two Integers, returns their product\nBiFunction <Integer, Integer, Integer> multiply = (a, b) -> a * b;\n\n// --- do not edit below this line ---\nassert toUpper.apply(\"java\").equals(\"JAVA\")  : \"toUpper failed\";\nassert isEven.test(4)                        : \"isEven(4) should be true\";\nassert !isEven.test(7)                       : \"isEven(7) should be false\";\nassert greeter.get().equals(\"hello\")         : \"greeter failed\";\nprinter.accept(\"test\");\nassert multiply.apply(3, 4) == 12            : \"multiply(3,4) should be 12\";\nSystem.out.println(\"1b passed!\");",
      "metadata": {
        "language": "java",
        "id": "code-1b",
        "executionSummary": {
          "executionOrder": 10,
          "success": true
        }
      },
      "execution_count": 10,
      "outputs": [
        {
          "output_type": "execute_result",
          "data": {
            "text/plain": ">> test\r\n1b passed!\r\n"
          },
          "metadata": {},
          "execution_count": 10
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": "md-1c",
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": "### Exercise 1c — Predict the output\n\n**Before running** this cell, read the stream pipeline carefully and write down what you expect `result` to be.\n\nThen run the cell. Were you right?\n\nThink about: what does each intermediate operation do to the stream? In what order does the `filter` remove elements?",
      "metadata": {
        "language": "markdown",
        "id": "md-1c"
      }
    },
    {
      "id": "code-1c",
      "cell_type": "code",
      "source": "import java.util.*;\nimport java.util.stream.*;\n\nList<String> words = List.of(\"banana\", \"apple\", \"cherry\", \"apricot\", \"blueberry\");\n\nlong result = words.stream()\n    .filter(w -> w.startsWith(\"a\"))\n    .count();\n\n// Write your prediction as a comment here before running:\n// My prediction: result = 2\n\nSystem.out.println(\"result = \" + result);",
      "metadata": {
        "language": "java",
        "id": "code-1c",
        "executionSummary": {
          "executionOrder": 2,
          "success": true
        }
      },
      "execution_count": 2,
      "outputs": [
        {
          "output_type": "execute_result",
          "data": {
            "text/plain": "result = 2\r\n"
          },
          "metadata": {},
          "execution_count": 2
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": "md-1d",
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": "### Exercise 1d — Effectively final\n\nThe method below does **not** compile.\n\n**Task:** Read the error, understand why the lambda capture is invalid, and fix it with the smallest possible change — without removing the lambda or the assertion.\n\nHint: what does the lecture say about local variables used inside a lambda body? Does `limit` qualify?",
      "metadata": {
        "language": "markdown",
        "id": "md-1d"
      }
    },
    {
      "id": "code-1d",
      "cell_type": "code",
      "source": "import java.util.function.*;\nimport java.util.*;\nimport java.util.stream.*;\n\n// Do not move code outside this method.\nList<Integer> filterAbove(List<Integer> values) {\n    int limit = 10;\n    //limit = 10;  // this reassignment makes `limit` non-final\n    Predicate<Integer> bigEnough = n -> n > limit;\n    return values.stream().filter(bigEnough).collect(Collectors.toList());\n}\n\n// --- do not edit below ---\nvar result = filterAbove(List.of(3, 7, 12, 9, 2, 11));\nassert result.equals(List.of(12, 11)) : \"Expected [12, 11] but got \" + result;\nSystem.out.println(\"1d passed! result = \" + result);",
      "metadata": {
        "language": "java",
        "id": "code-1d",
        "executionSummary": {
          "executionOrder": 3,
          "success": true
        }
      },
      "execution_count": 3,
      "outputs": [
        {
          "output_type": "execute_result",
          "data": {
            "text/plain": "1d passed! result = [12, 11]\r\n"
          },
          "metadata": {},
          "execution_count": 3
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": "md-part2",
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": "---\n## Part 2 — Fill In One Line\n\nEach exercise has a pipeline with **one step missing**. Replace the placeholder (e.g. `REPLACE_THIS_WITH_YOUR_LAMBDA`) with your code to make the assertions pass.",
      "metadata": {
        "language": "markdown",
        "id": "md-part2"
      }
    },
    {
      "id": "md-2a",
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": "### Exercise 2a — `filter`\n\nKeep only the numbers greater than 10 from the list.",
      "metadata": {
        "language": "markdown",
        "id": "md-2a"
      }
    },
    {
      "id": "code-2a",
      "cell_type": "code",
      "source": "import java.util.*;\nimport java.util.stream.*;\n\nList<Integer> numbers = List.of(3, 15, 7, 22, 10, 11);\n\nList<Integer> result = numbers.stream()\n    .filter(x -> x > 10)\n    .collect(Collectors.toList());\n\n// --- do not edit below ---\nassert result.equals(List.of(15, 22, 11)) : \"Expected [15, 22, 11] but got \" + result;\nSystem.out.println(\"2a passed! result = \" + result);",
      "metadata": {
        "language": "java",
        "id": "code-2a",
        "executionSummary": {
          "executionOrder": 4,
          "success": true
        }
      },
      "execution_count": 4,
      "outputs": [
        {
          "output_type": "execute_result",
          "data": {
            "text/plain": "2a passed! result = [15, 22, 11]\r\n"
          },
          "metadata": {},
          "execution_count": 4
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": "md-2b",
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": "### Exercise 2b — `map`\n\nConvert each string in the list to its length (as an `Integer`).",
      "metadata": {
        "language": "markdown",
        "id": "md-2b"
      }
    },
    {
      "id": "code-2b",
      "cell_type": "code",
      "source": "import java.util.*;\nimport java.util.stream.*;\n\nList<String> words = List.of(\"cat\", \"elephant\", \"ox\", \"giraffe\");\n\nList<Integer> lengths = words.stream()\n    .map(x -> x.length())\n    .collect(Collectors.toList());\n\n// --- do not edit below ---\nassert lengths.equals(List.of(3, 8, 2, 7)) : \"Expected [3, 8, 2, 7] but got \" + lengths;\nSystem.out.println(\"2b passed! lengths = \" + lengths);",
